# Application Security

Based on OWASP Top 10 and CWE Top 25.

## Input Validation
- Validate all external input at system boundaries
- Use Bean Validation annotations (`@NotNull`, `@Size`, `@Pattern`, `@Email`)
- Whitelist validation: define what IS allowed, not what is NOT
- Reject and log invalid input

## Injection Prevention
- SQL: parameterized queries or Spring Data methods only
- OS command: avoid `Runtime.exec()`; use ProcessBuilder with explicit args
- LDAP, XPath: parameterized APIs
- Log injection: strip newlines and control characters from user input

## Authentication
- Use proven frameworks (Spring Security) -- never roll your own
- Multi-factor authentication for sensitive operations
- Password storage: bcrypt or Argon2 with appropriate cost factor
- Account lockout after repeated failures

## Authorization
- Deny by default; explicitly grant access
- Principle of least privilege
- Server-side enforcement; never rely on client-side checks
- Audit log for authorization decisions

## Session Management
- Rotate session IDs after authentication
- HttpOnly, Secure, SameSite cookies
- Absolute and idle session timeouts
- Stateless tokens (JWT) for REST APIs with short expiry

## Secrets
- Never in source code, config files committed to VCS, or logs
- Use environment variables, vault services, or encrypted config
- Rotate regularly; support hot-reloading

## Dependency Security
- OWASP Dependency-Check in every build
- Subscribe to CVE feeds for direct dependencies
- Update vulnerable dependencies within SLA (critical: 24h, high: 7d)

## Error Handling
- Generic error messages to clients
- Detailed logging server-side with correlation IDs
- Never expose stack traces, class names, or internal paths

